<h3>1. Problem Statement</h3>
<ul>
    <li><b>What problem your system solves:</b> The system replaces error-prone manual tracking of shop inventory. It prevents stock-outs and inaccurate valuation by storing product quantities, real-time pricing, and total net worth dynamically.</li>
    <li><b>Who will use this system:</b> Shop owners, inventory managers, and store clerks who need a simplified dashboard to track physical goods.</li>
    <li><b>Why it is useful:</b> It automates necessary calculations, minimizes human error in manual entry, and offers persistent data tracking across usage sessions guaranteeing that business records are safe.</li>
    <li><b>What major functionalities are implemented:</b> Adding items, updating item details (price/stock), searching by Item ID, deleting outdated inventory items, file-based persistence, and generating an inventory value report.</li>
</ul>

<h3>2. Features Implemented</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Add record (Insert new stock items)</li>
    <li>Update record (Modify existing prices and quantities)</li>
    <li>Delete record (Remove discontinued products)</li>
    <li>Search functionality (Fetch product details by ID)</li>
    <li>File storage (using <code>fstream</code> to save/retrieve <code>inventory.txt</code>)</li>
    <li>Report generation (Lists all current inventory and aggregates total shop net worth)</li>
    <li>Input validation (Check for non-negative prices, proper lengths, and duplicate IDs)</li>
    <li>Transactions safety (Prevents accidental data loss by auto-saving changes)</li>
</ul>

<h3>3. System Design (OOP Architecture)</h3>

<h4>3.1 Class Definitions</h4>
<pre>class Product {
private:
    string productID;
    string name;
    double price;
    int quantity;

public:
    Product();
    Product(string id, string n, double p, int q);

    string getID() const;
    string getName() const;
    double getPrice() const;
    int getQuantity() const;

    void setQuantity(int q);
    void setPrice(double p);
    void display() const;
};

class InventoryManager {
private:
    vector&lt;Product&gt; products;
    string filename = "inventory.txt";
    int findIndex(const string&amp; id) const;

public:
    InventoryManager();
    ~InventoryManager();
    void loadFromFile();
    void saveToFile();
    void addRecord(string id, string name, double price, int qty);
    void updateRecord(string id, double price, int qty);
    void deleteRecord(string id);
    void searchRecord(string id) const;
    void generateReport() const;
};</pre>

<p><b>Explanation:</b></p>
<ul>
    <li><b>Why this class was created:</b> <code>Product</code> represents a single real-world item in the shop. <code>InventoryManager</code> is the controller class responsible for managing multiple products and communicating with the file system.</li>
    <li><b>Why data members are private:</b> To protect core item data (like <code>price</code> and <code>quantity</code>) from being modified directly or corrupted accidentally, adhering to the principle of Encapsulation.</li>
    <li><b>What each member function does:</b> Getters retrieve property info. Core manager functions (<code>addRecord</code>, <code>deleteRecord</code>, <code>updateRecord</code>) modify internal data structures and trigger <code>saveToFile()</code>.</li>
    <li><b>Why constructor is needed:</b> The <code>InventoryManager</code> constructor automatically triggers <code>loadFromFile()</code> ensuring the data stored previously is restored the moment the program launches.</li>
</ul>

<h4>3.2 Class Interaction Diagram / Explanation</h4>
<p><b>Explanation:</b></p>
<ul>
    <li><b>How classes interact with each other:</b> <code>InventoryManager</code> manages a list (<code>std::vector</code>) that holds <code>Product</code> objects.</li>
    <li><b>Which class controls system flow:</b> <code>InventoryManager</code> controls the entire system logic. Based on menu inputs, it performs actions on the stored list of products.</li>
    <li><b>How objects are created and used:</b> An <code>InventoryManager</code> object is instantiated in <code>main()</code>. <code>Product</code> objects are instantiated dynamically when a user adds a new item and appended to the vector.</li>
    <li><b>Whether you used composition or aggregation:</b> <b>Composition</b>. The <code>InventoryManager</code> is composed of <code>vector&lt;Product&gt;</code>. If the manager is destroyed, the vector managing the active products in-memory is also destroyed.</li>
</ul>

<h4>3.3 Constructor and Encapsulation Explanation</h4>
<p><b>Explanation:</b></p>
<ul>
    <li><b>How constructor initializes data:</b> The <code>Product</code> parameterized constructor assigns the provided ID, Name, Price, and Quantity directly into the class attributes at initialization.</li>
    <li><b>How private members are protected:</b> Attempting <code>myProduct.price = -10</code> fails at compilation. They can only be accessed through controlled public class member bounds.</li>
    <li><b>How data is accessed:</b> Access is strictly via explicit accessor methods (e.g., <code>getPrice()</code>) and mutator methods (<code>setPrice()</code>).</li>
    <li><b>Why encapsulation improves safety:</b> It prevents arbitrary data corruption (e.g., negative stock arrays causing invalid calculations) by restricting how an item's state changes.</li>
</ul>

<h4>3.4 STL Usage</h4>
<p><b>Explanation:</b></p>
<ul>
    <li><b>Which STL container was used:</b> <code>std::vector</code> and <code>std::string</code>.</li>
    <li><b>Why it was chosen:</b> Needs dynamic adjustments (adding/deleting goods). Vectors do not have a fixed size restriction.</li>
    <li><b>How it simplifies implementation:</b> Using <code>push_back()</code> and <code>erase()</code> makes memory management transparent.</li>
    <li><b>Difference between array (C) and vector (C++):</b> C-arrays have a fixed size defined at compilation and no bounds checking functionalities. <code>std::vector</code> naturally grows in size and offers helper functions.</li>
</ul>

<h4>3.5 File Handling Design (Using fstream)</h4>
<p><b>Explanation:</b></p>
<ul>
    <li><b>File name used:</b> <code>inventory.txt</code></li>
    <li><b>Data storage format:</b> Comma-Separated Values (CSV format).</li>
    <li><b>How data is written to file:</b> An <code>ofstream</code> loops through the <code>vector</code> and writes each item formatting it directly into a single line separating elements by commas. Overwrites on every save point to ensure the array state perfectly mirrors the persistent state.</li>
    <li><b>How data is read back:</b> An <code>ifstream</code> opens the file, reads line by line using <code>getline()</code>, and uses a <code>stringstream</code> to split the string by commas, casting them back to their appropriate datatypes and initializing objects.</li>
    <li><b>Example record stored in file:</b> <code>1001,Laptop,750.50,15</code></li>
    <li><b>Text file used:</b> Yes</li>
    <li><b>Append mode used:</b> No, we overwrite the whole text structure (<code>std::ios::trunc</code> by default via <code>ofstream</code>) ensuring modifications/deletions don't leave residual ghost items.</li>
    <li><b>Error handling implemented:</b> The program checks <code>file.is_open()</code> before parsing to prevent crash loops when starting a brand new stock instance organically.</li>
</ul>

<h3>4. Program Flow Explanation</h3>
<ul>
    <li><b>How menu works:</b> Built inside a <code>do-while</code> loop wrapped around a <code>switch(choice)</code> block. Users input numerical commands to traverse options.</li>
    <li><b>How object is created:</b> Data flows from <code>cin</code> to local tracking variables in <code>main()</code>, then passed into <code>manager.addRecord()</code> which creates the object.</li>
    <li><b>How adding works:</b> Performs a duplication check; if <code>false</code>, invokes <code>push_back</code> and auto-triggers <code>saveToFile</code>.</li>
    <li><b>How search works:</b> Uses a sequential check loop in <code>findIndex()</code> and outputs matching attributes via <code>Product::display()</code>.</li>
    <li><b>How update/delete works:</b> Finds vector index, alters parameters using setters or uses <code>erase()</code>, and applies persistence wrapper.</li>
    <li><b>How reports are generated:</b> Loops over all existing elements, invoking individual output and aggregating numeric totals for visual sum-ups.</li>
</ul>

<h3>5. OOP Concept Application</h3>
<ul>
    <li><b>Object-Oriented Design:</b> Real-life entities (Items/Products) are logically represented as distinct code blocks (<code>class</code>).</li>
    <li><b>Encapsulation &amp; Data Hiding:</b> Member variables cannot be touched directly, effectively placing a firewall between state tracking and execution layers.</li>
    <li><b>Modularity:</b> Using logical methods like <code>loadFromFile()</code>, making it so bugs isolating to file reading won't break the actual calculation methods.</li>
    <li><b>Reusability:</b> The class architecture makes it possible to simply inject this <code>.cpp</code> file directly inside an Emscripten target frame or another C++ API interface without breaking standard behaviors.</li>
    <li><b>Abstraction:</b> Implementation of <code>findIndex()</code> is hidden within manager layer so internal iteration isn't exposed to <code>main()</code>.</li>
    <li><b>Why C++ over C for this project:</b> Because C structures (<code>struct</code>) don’t encapsulate behaviors out of the box and lack memory safety like STL bounds logic. Object-oriented data mapping matches real business needs cleanly.</li>
</ul>

