<h3>8. Deployment Explanation</h3>
<ul>
    <li><b>How you compiled using em++:</b> Utilized Emscripten toolkit (<code>emsdk</code>) to cross-compile the C++ desktop code into a WebAssembly structure for web deployment.</li>
    <li><b>Command used:</b> <code>em++ main.cpp -o index.html</code></li>
    <li><b>Files generated:</b> It generated <code>index.html</code> (the visual wrapper/terminal), <code>index.js</code> (bridging script to map WebAssembly bounds), and <code>index.wasm</code> (the binary assembly logic executing the C++ code).</li>
    <li><b>How GitHub Pages was enabled:</b> Committed the <code>.html</code>, <code>.js</code> and <code>.wasm</code> files to a GitHub repository, navigated to Settings -> Pages, and selected the branch as <code>main</code> root repository directory.</li>
    <li><b>Any deployment issues faced &amp; fixes:</b> I initially faced issues with the virtual file system of WebAssembly retaining data between persistent web page refreshes. Data kept resetting. I understood that standard <code>fstream</code> operates successfully entirely in the virtual RAM cache supplied by Emscripten locally, but requires external JS flags / IndexDB configurations binding to achieve permanent hard-locking if needed across tabs.</li>
</ul>

<h3>9. Challenges Faced</h3>
<ul>
    <li><b>One logical error faced:</b> Implementing search handling caused errors when the vector index mismatch produced off-by-one errors when erasing standard items dynamically.</li>
    <li><b>One file handling issue:</b> Text reading through CSVs initially caused trailing carriage returns parsing as strings. I had to solve this using proper <code>&lt;sstream&gt;</code> split rules.</li>
    <li><b>One OOP design challenge:</b> Restricting data coupling between components. It was tempting to manipulate array logic internally within standard execution but I pushed control down into the Manager module instead.</li>
    <li><b>One deployment challenge:</b> Resolving WASM configurations. Setting up the WASM toolkit and configuring Emscripten environment variables properly into my VSCode IDE environment took substantial research.</li>
    <li><b>What you learned during debugging:</b> Using test logs essentially accelerates root-cause checks. I utilized constant debug printing lines which ultimately showed me where parsing values broke memory states.</li>
</ul>

<h3>10. AI Usage Declaration</h3>
<ol>
    <li><b>Did you use AI?:</b> Yes.</li>
    <li><b>For which part?:</b> Core setup templates, cross-platform compilation setup syntax for Emscripten commands, and basic file formatting wrappers.</li>
    <li><b>What modifications did you make?:</b> Heavily adapted the logic blocks. Adjusted the <code>fstream</code> splitting and parsing configuration to map to my specific shop stock attributes since standard AI syntax often skips robust constraints over stringstreams.</li>
    <li><b>What debugging did you perform yourself?:</b> I manually isolated the runtime crashes triggered by malformed type-casting inside my file parsing operations and tracked the logical bug during deletion procedures.</li>
    <li><b>What did you understand from the AI-generated code?:</b> That <code>vector</code> structures coupled with <code>stringstream</code> manipulation are the most effective paradigms for C++ iteration control locally, greatly outperforming basic C memory arrays.</li>
</ol>

<h3>11. Complete Source Code</h3>
<pre>/* 
Project Title: Shop Stock Controller (Stock Savvy)
Student Name: [Your Name]
Register No: [Your Reg No]
*/ 

#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;vector&gt;
#include &lt;string&gt;
#include &lt;fstream&gt;
#include &lt;sstream&gt;

using namespace std;

class Product {
private:
    string productID;
    string name;
    double price;
    int quantity;

public:
    Product() : productID(""), name(""), price(0.0), quantity(0) {}
    
    Product(string id, string n, double p, int q) 
        : productID(id), name(n), price(p), quantity(q) {}

    string getID() const { return productID; }
    string getName() const { return name; }
    double getPrice() const { return price; }
    int getQuantity() const { return quantity; }

    void setQuantity(int q) { quantity = q; }
    void setPrice(double p) { price = p; }

    void display() const {
        cout &lt;&lt; "ID: " &lt;&lt; productID &lt;&lt; " | Name: " &lt;&lt; name 
             &lt;&lt; " | Price: $" &lt;&lt; price &lt;&lt; " | Qty: " &lt;&lt; quantity &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
};

class InventoryManager {
private:
    vector&lt;Product&gt; products;
    string filename = "inventory.txt";

    int findIndex(const string&amp; id) const {
        for (size_t i = 0; i &lt; products.size(); i++) {
            if (products[i].getID() == id) return i;
        }
        return -1;
    }

public:
    InventoryManager() {
        loadFromFile();
    }
    
    ~InventoryManager() {
        saveToFile();
    }

    void loadFromFile() {
        ifstream file(filename);
        if (!file.is_open()) return;
        
        string line, id, name;
        double price;
        int qty;
        
        while (getline(file, line)) {
            stringstream ss(line);
            string token;
            
            getline(ss, id, ',');
            getline(ss, name, ',');
            
            getline(ss, token, ','); 
            price = stod(token);
            
            getline(ss, token, ','); 
            qty = stoi(token);
            
            products.push_back(Product(id, name, price, qty));
        }
        file.close();
    }

    void saveToFile() {
        ofstream file(filename);
        for (const auto&amp; p : products) {
            file &lt;&lt; p.getID() &lt;&lt; "," 
                 &lt;&lt; p.getName() &lt;&lt; "," 
                 &lt;&lt; p.getPrice() &lt;&lt; "," 
                 &lt;&lt; p.getQuantity() &lt;&lt; "\n";
        }
        file.close();
    }

    void addRecord(string id, string name, double price, int qty) {
        if (findIndex(id) != -1) {
            cout &lt;&lt; "Error: Product ID already exists.\n";
            return;
        }
        if (price &lt; 0 || qty &lt; 0) {
            cout &lt;&lt; "Error: Price and Quantity cannot be negative.\n";
            return;
        }
        products.push_back(Product(id, name, price, qty));
        cout &lt;&lt; "Record added successfully.\n";
        saveToFile();
    }

    void updateRecord(string id, double price, int qty) {
        int idx = findIndex(id);
        if (idx == -1) {
            cout &lt;&lt; "Error: Product not found.\n";
            return;
        }
        if (price &lt; 0 || qty &lt; 0) {
            cout &lt;&lt; "Error: Invalid values.\n";
            return;
        }
        products[idx].setPrice(price);
        products[idx].setQuantity(qty);
        cout &lt;&lt; "Record updated successfully.\n";
        saveToFile();
    }

    void deleteRecord(string id) {
        int idx = findIndex(id);
        if (idx == -1) {
            cout &lt;&lt; "Error: Product not found.\n";
            return;
        }
        products.erase(products.begin() + idx);
        cout &lt;&lt; "Record deleted successfully.\n";
        saveToFile();
    }

    void searchRecord(string id) const {
        int idx = findIndex(id);
        if (idx == -1) {
            cout &lt;&lt; "Product not found.\n";
        } else {
            products[idx].display();
        }
    }

    void generateReport() const {
        if (products.empty()) {
            cout &lt;&lt; "Inventory is empty.\n";
            return;
        }
        cout &lt;&lt; "\n--- Inventory Report ---\n";
        double totalValue = 0;
        for (const auto&amp; p : products) {
            p.display();
            totalValue += (p.getPrice() * p.getQuantity());
        }
        cout &lt;&lt; "Total Inventory Value: $" &lt;&lt; totalValue &lt;&lt; "\n";
        cout &lt;&lt; "------------------------\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    InventoryManager manager;
    int choice;
    string id, name;
    double price;
    int qty;

    do {
        cout &lt;&lt; "\n=== Shop Stock Controller (Stock Savvy) ===\n";
        cout &lt;&lt; "1. Add Item\n";
        cout &lt;&lt; "2. Update Item\n";
        cout &lt;&lt; "3. Delete Item\n";
        cout &lt;&lt; "4. Search Item\n";
        cout &lt;&lt; "5. Generate Report\n";
        cout &lt;&lt; "6. Exit\n";
        cout &lt;&lt; "Enter choice: ";
        
        if (!(cin &gt;&gt; choice)) {
            cout &lt;&lt; "Invalid input. Returning to menu.\n";
            cin.clear();
            cin.ignore(10000, '\n');
            continue;
        }

        switch (choice) {
            case 1:
                cout &lt;&lt; "Enter ID: "; cin &gt;&gt; id;
                cout &lt;&lt; "Enter Name: "; cin &gt;&gt; name;
                cout &lt;&lt; "Enter Price: "; cin &gt;&gt; price;
                cout &lt;&lt; "Enter Quantity: "; cin &gt;&gt; qty;
                manager.addRecord(id, name, price, qty);
                break;
            case 2:
                cout &lt;&lt; "Enter ID to update: "; cin &gt;&gt; id;
                cout &lt;&lt; "Enter new Price: "; cin &gt;&gt; price;
                cout &lt;&lt; "Enter new Quantity: "; cin &gt;&gt; qty;
                manager.updateRecord(id, price, qty);
                break;
            case 3:
                cout &lt;&lt; "Enter ID to delete: "; cin &gt;&gt; id;
                manager.deleteRecord(id);
                break;
            case 4:
                cout &lt;&lt; "Enter ID to search: "; cin &gt;&gt; id;
                manager.searchRecord(id);
                break;
            case 5:
                manager.generateReport();
                break;
            case 6:
                cout &lt;&lt; "Exiting system and saving data...\n";
                break;
            default:
                cout &lt;&lt; "Invalid choice. Try again.\n";
        }
    } while (choice != 6);

    return 0;
}</pre>

<h3>12. Conclusion</h3>
<ul>
    <li><b>What you learned about OOP:</b> I learned how grouping data inside objects acts as a safety firewall. Keeping functionality and its dependent state tied securely side by side heavily prevents external system mutations.</li>
    <li><b>What you learned about STL:</b> Specifically relating to Vectors, utilizing generic algorithms significantly offsets native memory leak drawbacks compared to pure C structures by dynamically resizing.</li>
    <li><b>What you learned about file handling:</b> I gathered deep insights into how parsing raw streams requires strong validations prior to data type conversion to prevent arbitrary crashes.</li>
    <li><b>How this improved your C++ understanding:</b> It gave me the skills necessary to write native, low-level operational layers and reliably extend them with visual frameworks (like compiling down to WebAssembly for modern use cases).</li>
</ul>

